Rating: 3
I "clip" recipes and this one has been on file awaiting trial since it was published in Bon Appetit in 2/2000. My husband and our guest remarked on the moisture of the chicken and the delicious flavor added by the crust. I prepared the recipe exactly as written. RE: dryness and flavor: - I think that it is important to understand that commercially prepared dried breadcrumbs cannot be substituted for the fresh French bread crumbs called for without totally changing the character and outcome of the recipe. The moisture of the rough, fresh crumbs combined with the 2 tablespoons of olive oil drained from the tomatoes will adhere very well to the surface of the chicken when it is pressed into place. Be sure to adequately season the chicken with salt and freshly ground pepper, as directed. Also, it is important to note that a bone in chicken breast maintains moisture better and has better flavor than a boneless one&and the presentation is more attractive. The only reason that I did not give the recipe 4 stars is that there was an issue with the particles of sun-dried tomatoes on the surface of the crust becoming very dark (bordering on burnt) in contrast to the bread crumbs before the chicken was fully cooked. When I noticed that this was happening, I placed a sheet of foil loosely over the chicken and that seemed to do the trick. Next time I will watch carefully and add the foil shield earlier (or perhaps reduce the temperature to 350° after 15 minutes.

